    <!-- ============================================
         CONVERGENCE
         ============================================ -->
    
    <div class="panel">
      <h4>Why This Matters</h4>
      <p>Every previous movement has been asking the same question: who will finally succeed where Adam, Noah, Abraham, Moses, David, and Israel failed? The New Testament answers with one name. Jesus is not merely part of God's plan; He is its fulfillment — every storyline converges in Him.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Scorecard:</strong> ✓ Image anointed · ✓ Waters passed · ✓ Test passed · ✓ Torah taught from the mountain · ✓ Temple in person · ✓ Curse borne on the tree · ✓ Veil torn · ✓ Garden tomb · ✓ Day one of new creation</div>

    <section class="theology-card" id="convergence">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">✨</span> Where Every Wire Converges</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God… All things were made through him.
        <span class="reference">John 1:1, 3</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Each Gospel opens by plugging Jesus into the story this suite has been tracing. John begins at Genesis 1:1 — "In the beginning" — and names Jesus as the Word through whom all things were made: the Creator entering creation. Matthew opens with "the book of the genealogy" (<em>biblos geneseos</em>, Genesis language) of the son of David, the son of Abraham — Movements 5 and 3 in one verse. Luke runs the genealogy the other way, back through David and Abraham to "Adam, the son of God" (Luke 3:38) — a designed line of seventy-seven generations whose sevenths land on Enoch, Abraham, and David, with Jesus arriving in the seventy-seventh position: the consummation of the whole human story from Adam onward — and Mark announces "the beginning of the gospel" with the kingdom arriving in power. Four openings, one claim: this is not a new story. It is <em>the</em> story reaching its protagonist.</p>
      <p>The title itself carries the freight. <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">מָשִׁיחַ</span> (<em>mashiach</em>, Messiah; Greek <em>christos</em>) means "anointed one" — and anointing, in the Bible's opening movements, is what marks the human <em>image</em> installed in sacred space. Adam and Eve are the prototype: God's living images, serving as royal priests in the garden-temple. Aaron is dressed and anointed as a walking Eden-figure to stand in the Tabernacle. Kings are anointed to rule as God's son (Ps 2:2, 7). To confess Jesus as <em>the</em> Anointed is to say the true image has finally arrived: the one Adam, Aaron, and David were sketches of — "the image of the invisible God, the firstborn over all creation" (Col 1:15).</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Not merely the rescuer — the pattern's original.</strong>
        Colossians 1:15–20 sings the movement in two stanzas around one Christ: all things created <em>through him and for him</em>, and all things reconciled <em>through him</em> — "making peace by the blood of his cross." Creation and new creation share one agent. The image of God is not a role Jesus fills; it is a face the previous bearers were borrowing.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE OVERLAP
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="overlap">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🏛️</span> The Overlap of Heaven and Earth in Person</h2>
      <p>Movement 1 established the Bible's geography: heaven and earth are not sealed realms but overlap at chosen points — Eden, Bethel, Sinai, the Tabernacle, the Temple. John's Gospel announces that the overlap now walks: "the Word became flesh and <em>tabernacled</em> (<span class="greek" lang="grc">ἐσκήνωσεν</span>, <em>eskēnōsen</em>) among us, and we beheld his <em>glory</em>" (John 1:14) — Exodus 40 vocabulary, the glory-cloud and the tent, applied to a human being. What filled the Tabernacle and Solomon's house, and what Ezekiel watched leave eastward, is present again — not behind a veil but at wedding feasts and wells.</p>
      <p>John then runs the temple thread through his whole Gospel. Jesus stands in Herod's courts and says "destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up… he was speaking of the temple of his body" (2:19–21). He offers living water to a Samaritan woman and announces worship no longer tied to either mountain (ch. 4); at the feast he cries that rivers of living water will flow from within (7:37–39) — Ezekiel 47's temple-river re-sourced in a person; lifted up, his pierced body releases water (19:34). Jesus is the sacred space the whole story has been building, the true Bethel — "you will see heaven opened, and the angels of God ascending and descending on the Son of Man" (1:51).</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Summary:</strong> Eden → Tabernacle → Temple → <em>Christ</em>. The line of sacred spaces the suite has traced does not end in a building. It ends in a body — and Movement 8 will extend that body into a people.</div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         THE TEST PASSED
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="test">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🏜️</span> Through the Waters, Into the Test</h2>
      <p>Jesus' public story opens with the suite's two most familiar scenes, replayed in order. First the waters: he comes up out of the Jordan, the Spirit — the <em>ruach</em> of Genesis 1:2, Exodus 14:21, and Ezekiel 37:9 — descends over the water, and the Father's voice declares the beloved Son (Mark 1:9–11). It is the creation-and-exodus pattern concentrated on one man, and it answers Movement 2's flood question directly: here at last is one who passes through the waters with heaven's verdict spoken over him. The verdict itself is a braid of three scriptures — the enthroned son of Psalm 2:7, the beloved son of Genesis 22:2, the Spirit-endowed servant of Isaiah 42:1 — king, Isaac, and suffering servant fused into one address. The Jordan is an ordination: the royal priest the whole story has waited for, anointed not in the Temple by Caiaphas's line but in the wilderness by the Spirit.</p>
      <p>Then, immediately, the test — and the narrative geography is deliberate. Adam was tested in a garden with every provision and failed; Israel was tested in the wilderness for forty years, fed daily, and failed; Jesus is driven into the wilderness, fasting forty days, and <em>stands</em>. Each temptation strikes the Eden fault line — provision, protection, rule on the tempter's terms — and each answer comes from Israel's wilderness scriptures (Deut 6–8), the faithful son reciting the lessons the first son refused to learn. Where Genesis 3 ends with grasping, Matthew 4 ends with the serpent's heir dismissed and angels ministering. The long question of Movements 2–6 — <em>where is the faithful image-bearer?</em> — has its answer standing in the desert.</p>
      <div class="cross-ref"><strong>Cross-reference:</strong> The tests do not end in the wilderness. Gethsemane is a garden at night, a will surrendered where Adam's grasped ("not my will, but yours"), and the mockers at the cross recycle the tempter's script: "if you are the Son of God…" (Matt 27:40). The last Adam is tested at a tree — and holds.</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE SERMON — the new Torah from the new mountain
         (Framing follows Mackie, The Messianic Torah
         Class Notes, BibleProject Classroom, 2025)
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="sermon">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">⛰️</span> The New Torah from the New Mountain</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        Do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them.
        <span class="reference">Matthew 5:17</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Between the wilderness test and the road to the cross, Matthew stages a scene the suite has watched before: a mountain, a mediator, and Torah for a newly formed people. Jesus "went up onto the mountain" (5:1) — Sinai's geometry replayed — and sat down to teach. But the mediator no longer relays; he legislates. Six times the sermon runs "you have heard it said… <em>but I say to you</em>," and when it ends, the crowds are amazed not because the teaching is foreign but because of its <em>authority</em> (7:28–29): this Moses speaks as the Lawgiver. The greater-Moses thread that began at the Jordan reaches its full height here — not a prophet carrying tablets down the mountain, but the covenant God teaching from it in person.</p>
      <p>And what he teaches is Movement 6's promise turned livable. "Fulfill the Torah and Prophets" points past legal technicality to the new-covenant hope the prophets staked everything on: the circumcised heart of Deuteronomy 30, the Torah written on hearts of Jeremiah 31, the new heart and indwelling Spirit of Ezekiel 36. The sermon is a portrait of that new-hearted humanity — anger, lust, retaliation, and enemy-love traced back to the heart the prophets said God would remake. Its blessings speak the same dialect: the meek "inherit the land" (5:5, drawing on Psalm 37's afflicted-inherit-the-land hope), the mourners are comforted in the cadence of Isaiah's great reversal (Isa 61; 65) — the very texts Movement 6 ends on — and the pure in heart "see God," the Psalms' old longing to return to Eden and ascend the mountain of the presence.</p>
      <p>Even the sermon's images run on creation current. "You are the light of the world" reaches through Isaiah back to day one (Gen 1:3) — God's people as bearers of the original light into the dark. The "city on a hill" that cannot be hidden gestures toward Isaiah 2's mountain-city with the nations streaming up to it — the destination Movement 9 will unveil. And the sermon closes as wisdom literature closes, with two ways and two builders: the wise one who hears and does, whose house stands on the rock. The one teaching is the one "through whom all things were made" — so of course his words bear the weight of a foundation.</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Not an entrance exam — a description.</strong>
        The sermon is not the price of admission to the kingdom; it is what kingdom-of-the-skies humanity looks like when heaven's rule takes up residence on earth. To live it is to taste new creation now, ahead of the final renewal — which is why the sermon sits here, between the faithful Adam proven in the desert and the curse absorbed at the tree.
      </div>
      <div class="cross-ref"><strong>Cross-reference:</strong> The mountain thread keeps climbing: glory revealed on a mountain (Matt 17) — flanked by Moses and Elijah, the two men who met the glory at Sinai/Horeb (Exod 33; 1 Kgs 19), now standing beside it in person — and the risen Lord commissioning his people <em>from</em> a mountain (Matt 28:16–20) — the new Moses sending a new people out with Torah for the nations, the hinge into Movement 8.</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE TREE
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="cross">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">✝️</span> The Curse and the Tree</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us — for it is written, "Cursed is everyone who is hanged on a tree" — so that in Christ Jesus the blessing of Abraham might come to the Gentiles.
        <span class="reference">Galatians 3:13–14</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>The Gospels stage the final week as the suite's threads pulled taut. Jesus descends the Mount of Olives — the mountain <em>east</em> of the city where Ezekiel watched the glory depart — and enters the Temple from the east as its rightful king, only to be rejected by it (Luke 19:29–48): the return of the glory, refused. Thorns, the ground's curse-sign since Genesis 3:18, are twisted into his crown. He is stripped and exposed, bearing the nakedness and shame of Genesis 3 in public. And he is hanged on a <em>tree</em> — Paul's word choice in Galatians 3 is exact — so that at a tree, where the curse entered, the curse is absorbed, and the blessing promised to Abraham (Movement 3) is released to the nations.</p>
      <p>The moment he dies, the narrative reaches for temple imagery: the veil — the woven cherubim barrier, Eden's flaming-sword guard rendered in fabric — is torn from top to bottom (Matt 27:51). The way back to the presence, barred since Genesis 3:24, stands open — and the traffic runs both directions: the blessing once guarded <em>in</em> can now flow <em>out</em>, the royal priest's final act releasing Eden's life from the sanctuary toward all creation, a current Movements 8 and 9 will follow to the ends of the earth. The covenant logic of Genesis 15 completes itself here: the God who passed between the pieces alone now absorbs, alone, the covenant's death-curse in His own person. Grace signed the covenant; grace pays it.</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>De-creation, volunteered for.</strong>
        Darkness at noon, the earth shaking, the Son exiled outside the city — the cross gathers every de-creation image the suite has catalogued and lets them fall on the one man who did not deserve them. It is the flood, the exile, and the east-gate departure concentrated into three hours — endured this time from the inside, so that the cycle can finally break.
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         DAY ONE
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="resurrection">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🌱</span> The First Day of New Creation</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        Now on the first day of the week… she turned around and saw Jesus standing there… Supposing him to be the gardener…
        <span class="reference">John 20:1, 14–15</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>John dates the resurrection twice in one chapter — "the first day of the week" (20:1, 19) — and locates it precisely: "in the place where he was crucified there was a <em>garden</em>, and in the garden a new tomb" (19:41). Mary's mistake is John's theology: she supposes him to be the gardener, and she is more right than she knows. On day one, in a garden, the true Adam is back at his work. The resurrection is not merely the vindication of an innocent man or proof of life after death. It is the first slab of the new creation laid in the middle of history — a human body gone through death and out the other side, never to die again, "the firstborn from the dead" (Col 1:18), "the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep" (1 Cor 15:20).</p>
      <p>That evening Jesus stands among his disciples and <em>breathes on them</em>: "Receive the Holy Spirit" (20:22) — Genesis 2:7 and Ezekiel 37 enacted, the risen Adam breathing life into a new humanity. Paul draws the conclusion the whole suite has been building toward: "the first man Adam became a living being; the last Adam became a life-giving spirit" (1 Cor 15:45). Adam received life; the last Adam gives it. Everything Ezekiel promised — new heart, indwelling Spirit, resurrection, returned glory — now exists in one person, and the question of the remaining movements is simply distribution.</p>
      <p>Luke stages his own day-one scene, and he writes it in Genesis 3's exact grammar. Two people walk with God-in-their-midst and cannot perceive it — "their eyes were prevented" (24:16). Then comes a meal: he takes bread, blesses it, breaks it, gives it — "and their eyes were opened, and they recognized him" (24:31). The wording is Genesis 3:6–7 played in reverse: there, two humans took and ate, "and the eyes of the two of them were opened, and they recognized" — their nakedness, their shame. At Emmaus the first meal of the new creation undoes the meal that broke the old one. Eyes open again over taken-and-eaten food, but this time recognition brings communion instead of hiding — and the risen one is known, ever after, "in the breaking of the bread" (24:35).</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Summary:</strong> Waters → dry land → breath → garden → day one. The resurrection narratives are written in the suite's oldest vocabulary because they are its hinge: everything before was promise; everything after is spread.</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         TRAJECTORY
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="forward">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🧭</span> Trajectory: One New Human — Then a New Humanity</h2>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="panel"><h4>What advances</h4><p>The faithful image-bearer exists. The test is passed, the curse absorbed, the veil torn, the covenant kept from both sides, and new creation has begun — bodily, datably, in a garden. Every promise of Movement 6 is now embodied in one risen person.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>What remains unsolved</h4><p>One renewed human is not yet a renewed humanity, and a torn veil is not yet a filled world. The commission of Genesis 1:28 — fill the earth — still stands, waiting for the risen Lord's life to be distributed. He tells his disciples to wait in Jerusalem for power.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="panel"><h4>Echoes Fulfilled</h4><p>New Adam · true Israel · greater Moses · greater David · true Temple · image of God · firstborn of new creation — every prior office lands on one person (Rom 5; Matt 2–4; John 2; Luke 1:32; Col 1:15–20).</p></div>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="panel"><h4>What Changed?</h4><p><strong>Before:</strong> Humanity searched for a faithful representative.<br><strong>After:</strong> The faithful human has come — and risen.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>Echoes Ahead</h4><p>Fire falling on many heads (Acts 2) · the church as a temple of living stones (1 Cor 3:16; 1 Pet 2:5) · resurrection as firstfruits of the full harvest (1 Cor 15:20–23) · the Lamb on the throne and the wedding of heaven and earth (Rev 5; 21–22).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Project Context Insight: one story, two volumes.</strong>
        Luke wrote this movement and the next as a single continuous work — Luke-Acts — and he teaches less by argument than by juxtaposition: paired characters, mirrored trials, deliberate reversals across both volumes. If you want to see that architecture mapped pair by pair, explore the <a href="luke-acts-contrast-atlas-index.html">Luke–Acts Contrast Atlas</a> here on Project Context.
      </div>
      <div class="pivot-box">
        <span class="pivot-label">Where the Story Goes Next</span>
        <p>Forty days of kingdom teaching, an ascension to the throne, and a command to wait. Movement 8 opens in an upper room at a harvest festival, when the fire that once filled the Tabernacle falls again — this time in <em>many</em> flames, on many heads.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="takeaway">Jesus is not a new character introduced to salvage an old plot. He is the plot: Creator, true image, walking temple, faithful Adam — and on the first day of the week, the new creation's firstborn.</p>
    </section>

